 You’re welcome. What’s your name?\nClara: I’m Clara. What’s your name?\nJohn: I’m John.\nClara: Where are you from, John?\nJohn: I’m from here. And you?\nClara: I’m from Cambridge. Where do you live here?\nJohn: I stay in a dorm on Keppel Street. What about you?\nClara: I live in a flat on Museum Street.\nJohn: How old are you?\nClara: I’m 18. And you?\nJohn: I’m 20. We’re here!\nClara: Shall we have a coffee after class?\nJohn: Sure! I’ll give you a call after class. What’s your number?\nClara: Great! My number is 2071484567.\nJohn: I’ll call you. See you!\nClara: See you!',420,2,'en','2026-02-17 20:03:41'),(12,'On the Phone','Phone conversation and communication dialogues','https://player.vimeo.com/video/1147680353','Jane: Hello.\nJohn: Hi, Clara.\nJane: Excuse me, who is this?\nJohn: This is John. Who am I talking to?\nJane: This is Jane Feathers.\nJohn: Isn’t this 555 006 7192?\nJane: No, this is 555 006 7182\nJohn: Oh! I’m sorry. It’s the wrong number.\nJane: No problem, goodbye!\nClara: Hello!\nJohn: Clara?\nClara: Yes, this is Clara.\nJohn: Hi, Clara. This is John.\nClara: Hey John! How are you?\nJohn: I am fine, thank you. How are you?\nClara: I’m fine too.\nJohn: Do you have time today?\nClara: Yes, I do.\nJohn: Will you come to the café with me?\nClara: That sounds great! What time?\nJohn: Half past one. Is that good for you?\nClara: Oh, I have a class at that time. My class ends at three. Does three o\'clock suit you?\nJohn: Yes, it does. See you at three then.\nClara: See you!',380,3,'en','2026-02-17 20:03:41'),(13,'At the University','Daily communication dialogues at university','assets/videos/en/4.mp4','Clara: Hello everyone!\nJohn: Hi! How are you?\nClara: Thanks, I\'m fine. And you?\nJohn: I\'m fine too. This is my friend Clara. She is from Cambridge.\nLucy: Hello Clara. I am Lucy. I\'m from Manchester.\nNick: Hi, Clara. I\'m Nick. I am from Derby.\nClara: Nice to meet you.\nNick: How old are you, Clara?\nClara: I\'m eighteen. And you?\nNick: Nineteen. But Lucy is twenty.\nJohn: I am older than you. I was born on December 20, 2002. I\'m twenty years old.\nClara: Then your zodiac sign is Sagittarius.\nJohn: Exactly. And what is your sign?\nClara: My sign is Aries. I was born in April.\nLucy: Good, I\'m a Pisces. I was born in March. So Clara, which department are you studying in?\nClara: I\'m studying English Language Teaching. I just enrolled. You?\nLucy: I\'m studying at the Faculty of Medicine.\nClara: What semester are you in?\nLucy: Second. And you?\nNick: It\'s my second semester in the Linguistics Department.\nClara: I am in my first semester.\nNick: Clara, what do you think about the English Language Teaching Department in London?\nClara: My classmates are good; the environment is very nice... It is good to study here.\nJohn: Oh my God! I\'m so late, sorry, I have class at 14.00.\nClara: Bye!\nJohn: See you!',360,4,'en','2026-02-17 20:03:41'),(14,'At the Supermarket','Shopping and asking prices at the supermarket','https://player.vimeo.com/video/1147653707','Clara: Excuse me, where are the potatoes?\nSeller: Over there, in the front, in the vegetable section.\nClara: I looked there but I couldn\'t see them.\nSeller: In front on the right, right at the entrance.\nClara: Thanks, let me look again.\nClara: Oh, John, what a nice coincidence!\nJohn: Yes.\nClara: I need to shop urgently. My fridge is empty.\nJohn: I want to buy fresh fruit and vegetables. Is there anything on sale right now?\nClara: Apples are on sale. Fuji apples. £1.80 a kilo.\nJohn: Good, one kilo please! Is there any spinach?\nClara: It’s over there, next to the onions.\nJohn: Thank you very much!\nClara: And did you get everything you wanted?\nJohn: I need a liter of milk, a can of coke and a bottle of water.\nClara: They are in the drinks aisle.\nJohn: Thank you.\nClara: Are you all set?\nJohn: Yes, thank you, that\'s all. Do you need anything?\nClara: Hmm. What do I need? Let me check my shopping list. I need a kilo of rice, a bunch of parsley, 250 grams of cheese, 100 grams of salami and a jar of honey.\nJohn: What kind of salami do you want?\nClara: Turkey salami.\nJohn: Salami is next to meat products, rice is next to grains, cheese is in the cheese aisle and parsley is next to vegetables and fruits. Look. Honey is in the sale section. Do you need anything else?\nClara: No, that\'s all. Now we can go to the checkout. Luckily, there isn’t a long line at the checkout.\nSeller: Do you want a plastic bag?\nClara: No, I have a bag.\nSeller: 12 Pounds 50 for all of them.\nClara: Here you go. I want to pay by card.\nSeller: Is your card contactless?\nClara: Yes.\nSeller: Hold your card to the POS device.\nSeller: Thank you very much. Have a nice day.\nJohn: Have a nice day!\nSeller: Good afternoon, would you like a bag?\nJohn: Yes, please.\nSeller: 8,75 please. Do you want to pay by card?\nJohn: I would like to pay in cash, please!\nSeller: Your change is 1,25.\nJohn: Thank you.\nClara: The shopping bags are very heavy.\nJohn: I\'ll help you home. Give me the bags!\nClara: Are you sure?\nJohn: Yes.\nClara: Thanks a lot for your help.',340,5,'en','2026-02-17 20:03:41'),(15,'At Home','Daily life dialogues at home','assets/videos/en/6.mp4','Clara: Welcome.\nJohn: Thanks for the invitation. Where can I hang my coat?\nClara: In the cupboard here.\nJohn: Thank you.\nClara: Please sit down, rest.\nJohn: Thank you.\nClara: Would you like to have a drink?\nJohn: I can have a coffee.\nClara: With or without milk?\nJohn: Without milk.\nClara: OK, I\'ll get it right away. This is your black coffee and this is my coffee with milk.\nJohn: Oh, thank you.\nClara: You\'re welcome!\nJohn: How big is the apartment?\nClara: 80 square metres.\nJohn: Isn\'t it too big for you alone? How many rooms does it have?\nClara: Not at all. This flat is perfect for me. It is very nice and quiet. It has a lounge, two bedrooms and a kitchen. It also has a bathroom and a balcony.\nJohn: Wow, it\'s great! How is the location?\nClara: It is very central. There is a bus stop and a shopping centre nearby.\nJohn: Do you own the flat?\nClara: No, I pay rent.\nJohn: Is it expensive?  How much do you pay a month?\nClara: No, it is cheap. The rent is £1500 and the monthly fee is about £80.\nJohn: It\'s not expensive and the flat is nice. It is on the 4th floor but there is no lift. That\'s why it\'s so cheap. Can I have a look around the flat?\nClara: Sure!\nClara: This is the corridor. Unfortunately, it\'s very narrow. There are two rooms here on the right.\nJohn: The rooms are quite bright.\nClara: Yes, that\'s right. There\'s a big living room opposite this one.\nJohn: The living room has a balcony.\nClara: Yes, but it\'s not big.\nJohn: Is this the kitchen?\nClara: Yes, the kitchen is useful and has a view of the river.\nJohn: Is this the bathroom?\nClara: Yes, small but bright.\nJohn: Does the house have a garage?\nClara: Yes, each flat in this apartment block has its own garage.\nJohn: Is the flat well heated?\nClara: Yes, this house is south facing and well insulated.\nJohn: The flat is very nice. It has everything you need.\nClara: Exactly, I am very happy with this flat.\nJohn: Now it\'s time to eat. Are you hungry? I know a good restaurant nearby. Shall we have dinner together?\nClara: I\'m starving. My stomach is rumbling.\nJohn: Come on then, let\'s go eat!',400,6,'en','2026-02-17 20:03:41'),(16,'At the Restaurant','Ordering food and paying the bill','https://player.vimeo.com/video/1147681670','John: We\'re finally here. Let\'s go inside.\nWaiter: Good afternoon, welcome to our restaurant. Do you have a reservation?\nJohn: No, I\'m afraid not. Do you have a free table for two?\nWaiter: Yes, no problem. Where would you like to sit?\nJohn: By the window, please.\nWaiter: Unfortunately, the tables by the window are reserved.\nClara: OK, a table at the entrance is fine for us.\nWaiter: Wait a minute! Yes, the table at the entrance is still empty. Please come in! Here is the one just round the cor